    <title type="text">Virgil's Garden: Hortus Virgilianus</title>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<a
      href="http://classics.uc.edu/~parker/hortus/vergilsgarden.html">Virgil's Garden: Hortus
      Virgilianus</a><br />Holt Parker <br /><blockquote
      class="tr_bq"><img
      alt="http://classics.uc.edu/~parker/hortus/cover%20page%20art/vergil.header.lg.gif"
      class="decoded" height="108"
      src="http://classics.uc.edu/%7Eparker/hortus/cover%20page%20art/vergil.header.lg.gif"
      width="320" /></blockquote><br /><blockquote class="tr_bq"><table
      style="height: 153px; width: 729px;"><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><div
      align="center"><span style="color: red; font-size: x-small;">Vergil's
      Garden</span></div></td> </tr><tr> <td><div
      align="center"><span style="color: red; font-size: x-small;">Hortus
      Vergilianus</span></div></td> <td><div align="center"><span
      style="color: red; font-size: x-small;">Le Jardin de
      Vergile</span></div></td> </tr><tr> <td><div
      align="center"><span style="color: red; font-size: x-small;">Il Giardino
      virgiliano</span></div></td> <td> <div align="center"><span
      style="color: red; font-size: x-small;">Die Planzenwelt Vergils
      </span></div></td> </tr></tbody></table><span
      style="font-size: x-small;">Vergil's Garden is an illustrated guide to the plants in
      Vergil's <em>Georgics</em>. I plan to expand the site later to include the
      <em>Eclogues</em> and <em>Aeneid</em>.</span>
      </blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span style="font-size: x-small;">You
      can enter and navigate in any number of ways.</span> </blockquote><blockquote
      class="tr_bq"><div align="center"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman, Times,
      serif; font-size: x-small;">Click on one of the link below to go to the text of the
      Georgics</span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman, Times, serif; font-size:
      x-small;">.</span></div><table border="1" style="height: 31px; width:
      506px;"> <tbody><tr> <td height="25" width="27%"> <span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://classics.uc.edu/~parker/hortus/geo1.shtml">GEORGICA&nbsp;
      I</a></span></td> <td height="25" width="24%"> <span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://classics.uc.edu/~parker/hortus/geo2.shtml">GEORGICA&nbsp;
      II</a></span></td> <td height="25" width="25%"> <span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://classics.uc.edu/~parker/hortus/geo3.shtml">GEORGICA&nbsp;
      III</a></span></td> <td height="25" width="24%"> <span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://classics.uc.edu/~parker/hortus/geo4.shtml">GEORGICA&nbsp;
      IV</a></span></td> </tr></tbody></table><span
      style="font-family: Times New Roman, Times, serif; font-size: x-small;">Each book is linked
      to the Latin text as broken up into segments at <a
      href="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cache/perscoll_Greco-Roman.html"
      target="_blank">Perseus</a> (with dictionary and parsing aids). You can set either
      Latin or English translation as your default there. The names of the plants are highlighted and
      a click will take you to a page with pictures of the plants, their scientific names (genus and
      species), and the common names in English, French, German, and Italian. Clicking the Latin name
      will take you to the entry in <a
      href="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0059"
      target="_blank">Lewis and Short</a>. Almost all links open in a new page, so you can
      have the text, the pretty pictures, etc., all open on your desktop. At the bottom of each page
      is a set of navigation links to return you to the main pages in that same window.
      </span></blockquote>]]></content>
